               <p>488. <persName id="def1-488-18650410" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-488-18650410" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-488-18650410" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-488-18650410" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-488-18650410" type="given" value="WILLIAM GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM GEORGE THOMPSON</hi> (20)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18650410-488-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18650410-488-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18650410-488-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="burglary"></interp>, Burglariously breaking and entering the dwelling-house of <persName id="t18650410-name-652" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-652" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-652" type="surname" value="FRANCE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-652" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18650410-488-offence-1 t18650410-name-652"></join>George France</persName>, and stealing therein 1 opera-glass, 1 coat, and 1 shirt, his property.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. THOMPSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-653" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-653" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-653" type="surname" value="FRANCE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-653" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE FRANCE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Ceylon-street, Battersea, with my father, who is a civil engineer—I have seen the prisoner in the Wandsworth-road—he called about a week before 30th March, and said that he could draw very well—I have seen him five or six times—the family went to bed on 30th March about 10 o'clock—I went over the house, and saw it safe—I came down between 6.30 and 7 next morning, and found the kitchen-window open</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186504100200"></xptr>
               <p>—I missed a pair of boots and opera-glass, a cloak, and a shirt, worth about 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—this is the opera-glass (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>),—here is a little scratch on it where I marked it for the sight; I know it by that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-654" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-654" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-654" type="surname" value="SMITHERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-654" type="given" value="ARTHUR"></interp>ARTHUR SMITHERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant to Mr. Clark, pawnbroker, of High-street, Clapham—this opera-glass was pledged there on 31st March by the prisoner in the name of William Thomas, Park-road—I afterwards picked him out from a number of others.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-655" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-655" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-655" type="surname" value="SAPPHILL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-655" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN SAPPHILL</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, V</hi> 342.) On 31st March I examined the prosecutor's premises, and found marks on the kitchen-window as if a knife had been put between the sashes to push the catch back—I made inquiries, and found the opera-glass at the pawnbroker's—I then went, in consequence of information, to 15, Finsbury-street, Blackfriars-road, and asked whether Mr. Thompson was in—I found the prisoner there, and charged him with the burglary—he said, "Very well"—he was placed with six or seven others at the station, and Smithers picked him out, and said, "That is the man that pledged the goods"—I said, "Go and touch him, "and he went and touched the prisoner, who made no reply—as I took him to the Police-court he that he had pawned the glasses.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> On 31st March I met William Thomas, who I had been with on several occasions; he asked me to pawn the glasses for him, which I did for 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and he gave me 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 11<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. I know nothing of the rob<lb></lb>bery.</p>
               <p>
